== macOS orthography ==

Hi Roy,

Thanks for approving [https://wiki.freecad.org/index.php?title=Download&diff=prev&oldid=1769126 my edit] of the Download page so quickly! I do have one note, and question, about [https://wiki.freecad.org/index.php?title=Download&diff=prev&oldid=1769223 the subsequent edit] you made that changed "macOS" to "MacOS".

As far as I know, Apple has never named or referred to their operating system as "MacOS" (capitalized, no space), as you edited it. It was originally just the "System" software, then "Mac OS" (when they started the clone hardware program), then "Mac OS X" (when they moved to the NeXTSTEP-derived codebase and increased the major version to 10, with the prior codebase qualified as the "Classic" Mac OS retroactively), then "OS X", and finally/currently "macOS" (first time without a space, but lower-case, presumably for consistency with their "iOS" operating system, and dropping the "X" coinciding with the major version increasing beyond 10).

I noticed that some other pages on this wiki, including translations of the Download page itself to other languages, sometimes use other forms, including some of the older canonical forms, so I'm not aware of any wiki-wide standard to be adhered to. (Though I would naively assume that, should consistency be desired, matching the current standard form, currently "macOS", would be preferred on new edits.) As well, the header above the line that you edited still uses the "macOS" form (which predates my edit).

So, while it's obviously not very serious as I imagine it's still clear enough to any reader, is there a reason to have changed the styling of the name to a notably non-standard form? [[User:Joseph Spiros|Joseph Spiros]] ([[User talk:Joseph Spiros|talk]]) 20:28, 25 March 2026 (UTC)

:Sentences start with a capital. If the first word in a sentence is 'macOS', it must be spelled a 'MacOS'. [[User:Roy 043|Roy 043]] ([[User talk:Roy 043|talk]]) 21:27, 26 March 2026 (UTC)
::Ah, I see, thanks for explaining your reasoning.
::In contemporary practice, I have observed an evolution beyond the strict sentence case rule you articulate.
::With so many new nouns and abbreviations that rely on non-standard capitalization, including even some humans preferring to be identified with lowercase names, some style guides have started to recommend prioritizing faithful reproduction of names or abbreviations that use non-standard capitalization over traditional sentence case rules. And of those that haven't adopted that approach and continue to prioritize sentence case above all, those guides nonethless tend to advise rewriting sentences to avoid the issue, to help ensure faithful reproduction and avoid ambiguity nonetheless.
::Wikipedia actually takes a somewhat middle-of-the-road approach, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Trademarks#Trademarks_that_begin_with_a_lowercase_letter carving out an exception for camelCase trademarks that in common usage begin with lowercase letters, especially if it's only a single lowercase letter prefix (though, with some longer exceptions, including macOS)], but [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Capital_letters#Items_that_require_initial_lower_case they notably retain sentence case priority for lowercase personal names].
::Here's a somewhat recent academic article (from 2020) that goes into detail about how contemporary English users typically relate to these cases (no pun intended): '''Patekar, J. (2020). A sentence need not begin with a capital letter. Strani jezici, 49(2), 155–176. [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doi_(identifier) doi]:[https://doi.org/10.22210%2Fstrjez%2F49-2%2F1 10.22210/strjez/49-2/1]'''.
::Anyway, if a more conservative approach is desired as the standard for this wiki, I'd humbly suggest a guideline to avoid unfaithful reproduction as much as possible by rewriting sentences to not start with affected names. If that's agreeable, I'd be happy to submit appropriate edits. [[User:Joseph Spiros|Joseph Spiros]] ([[User talk:Joseph Spiros|talk]]) 13:39, 3 April 2026 (UTC)
:::I can understand how this can be important to some. But for me, and IMO also for this Wiki, this is a minor issue, I would even say a non-issue. The current, common, standard of starting every sentence with a capital can be upheld. The fact that somebody in California decides on a name that does not start with a cap, is not good enough a reason to change that. I am sorry if that disappoints you. [[User:Roy 043|Roy 043]] ([[User talk:Roy 043|talk]]) 17:04, 5 April 2026 (UTC)
::::I think you may have misunderstood my comment's purpose. To be clear, your personal perspective on English orthography makes little difference to me, I simply share the information on the status quo should you find it useful. Since it inspired a minor edit by you to one of my edits, it seemed potentially important to you.
::::Whatever the case, my primary interest is clarity, both in the sense that I'm seeking clarity regarding this wiki's style guidelines/expectations, and in the sense that I'm expressing a preference for clarity in the faithful reproduction of names where possible.
::::So, if you are commenting authoritatively on this wiki's style guidelines, do you have a comment on my suggestion for additional guidance, along with the sentence case guideline that you've represented, that editors avoid starting sentences with names that would therefore be unfaithfully reproduced? And/or, whether it's a formal guideline or not, do you have any objection to my, or anyone, making edits that otherwise follow that approach?
::::All that really matters to me is that guidelines/expectations are reasonably clear, whatever they are, so that misunderstandings can be avoided. [[User:Joseph Spiros|Joseph Spiros]] ([[User talk:Joseph Spiros|talk]]) 18:28, 5 April 2026 (UTC)

